#X text 37 14 Envelopes are widely used to control the amplitude of sounds when triggered. The [decay~] object from ELSE is an extremely simple envelope with just an exponential decay stage. The envelope function starts at a maximum amplitude and just decays (until reaching 0). It can be triggered by bangs \, control data numbers and audio impulses or gates. Note that you don't need to worry much about clicks when enveloping a noisy or percussive sound!, f 82;
#X text 364 147 By the way \, you can use a decay envelope to implement a damped oscillator \, see:, f 31;
#X obj 243 181 sig~;
#X obj 243 152 tgl 19 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X text 272 234 The [lag2~] object \, with a 0 length ramp up and a decay ramp is a way to implement an exponential decay envelope when triggered by impulses (so no gates longer than one sample). Note it has the same one pole filter as [decay~]., f 49;
#N canvas 864 113 282 319 impulse 0;
#X obj 91 61 inlet;
#X obj 92 243 outlet~;
#X obj 92 201 vline~;
#X msg 92 92 1;
#X obj 109 134 delay 1 1 samps;
#X msg 109 158 0;
#X connect 0 0 3 0;
#X connect 2 0 1 0;
#X connect 3 0 4 0;
#X connect 3 0 2 0;
#X connect 4 0 5 0;
#X connect 5 0 2 0;
#X restore 403 447 pd impulse;
